/*********************************************** JAVA **********************************************/

Optimal Solution - We slide a fixed-size window over s2 while maintaining character frequencies and check if any window matches 
                    the frequency pattern of s1, indicating a permutation.


class Solution {
    public boolean checkInclusion(String s1, String s2) {
        int n = s1.length();
        int m = s2.length();
        // If s1 is longer than s2, permutation is impossible
        if (n > m) return false;
        // Frequency arrays for characters aâ€“z
        int[] s1_freq = new int[26];
        int[] s2_freq = new int[26];
        // Populate frequency of s1
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            s1_freq[s1.charAt(i) - 'a']++;
        }
        // Sliding window pointers
        int i = 0, j = 0;
        // Traverse s2 using sliding window of size n
        while (j < m) {
            // Add current character to window
            s2_freq[s2.charAt(j) - 'a']++;
            // If window size exceeds n, remove leftmost character
            if (j - i + 1 > n) {
                s2_freq[s2.charAt(i) - 'a']--;
                i++;
            }
            // If both frequency arrays match, permutation exists
            if (Arrays.equals(s1_freq, s2_freq)) {
                return true;
            }
            j++;
        }
        // No permutation found
        return false;
    }
}
Time Complexity :- O(m + n).
Space Complexity :- O(1).
